<username>CaliPharmGirl<//username><Date>1592658513672</Date><rating>1< /rating><Review>Unfortunately my previous optometrist retired a couple of years ago. He took care of my eyes for nearly a decade. Going to Stanton was my 2nd attempt at finding a replacement. üòï
I needed a contact lens exam. Suffice it to say, I'm still looking for another optometrist next time need an exam. If you want personal, attentive service don't go here. The exam is done without the physical presence of an optometrist which I didn't realize until I was taken to the room for the exam. Patients should be made aware of this immediately upon check in. I feel as if this fact was purposely hidden. The wait time was horrendous. They were out of a sample for my prescription contact lens. Plus they tried to force me to buy 6 months of contact lens without trying the prescription sample first. I had to tell the guy, "No!" twice before he accepted my answer as final.
Not the service I'm used to. Ask questions about the exam upon arrival so you know what you're getting into. Pro side, the guy who checked me in and did my pretest for glaucoma was friendly which made this bitter pill a little easier to swallow.</Review>< Pics>

Whatever you do, don't go here! They make it sound like they have all kinds of deals but when you arrive,all the pricing changes. When I first got there I was told it would be $115 of my $150 insurance allowance for my exam alone, but when I pushed back and said my insurance card says $20, suddenly they magically found some "new" pricing that made it $20. You don't get to see a real doctor, there was just someone on a video screen. They didn't ask me any of the usual questions I get when seeing an in person doctor and the exam was very limited. The prescription contacts they gave me were awful and I could not read anything with them in. I had to wear readers over them at all times. I called the next day and told them that the contacts didn't work and to cancel my order but they STILL billed my insurance for the box of contacts that I never picked up and that I cancelled less than 24 hours after leaving the exam. So I am out over $70 worth of contacts that I never received and told them I could not use. When I called to cancel the order I was told no problem since I cancelled within 48 hours of the exam and then they billed my insurance anyway and THEY got paid for the contacts that I never received. Now my insurance allowance for the year is used up and I still have no contacts  This is a SCAM! They try to swindle all the money they can out of you. Go somewhere else!

<review>I don‚Äôt really do negative reviews but in this case........
I went in for an eye exam to see if my prescription had changed, my distance vision is blurry but I have no problem reading fine print. My exam was conducted via tele conference with the doctor. Not what I‚Äôm used to but OK. After the exam I was told to pick out frames while we waited for the results. Knowing my insurance covers frames up to $100 I said sure. The associate then went over the results of my exam where I was shocked to learn the Doctor recommended progressive lenses to help me with my reading. Hmmmm, I then picked up the card they had on the counter to determine if you need glasses and read every line easily. The associate then went over what the glasses would cost me out of pocket after insurance. Needless to say I had already lost all confidence in the honesty of this establishment. When I told the associate I would not be making a decision right then they snapped ‚ÄúI thought you were here to buy glasses today ‚Äú I said ‚Äúno I came in for an eye exam.‚Äù The associate said they were going to get the manager to ‚Äúclose this sale.‚Äù I told them they were wasting their time and left. I felt like they were using pretty shady techniques to increase sales. I also saw 3 separate customers come in having problems with glasses they had purchased there. To their credit the problems were met with a ‚Äúlet‚Äôs get this fixed ‚Äú attitude but not exactly confidence inspiring. Original post as follows
________

These guys dont follow civil code 1954

1954. (a) A landlord may enter the dwelling unit only in the
following cases:
(1) In case of emergency.
(2) To make necessary or agreed repairs, decorations, alterations
or improvements, supply necessary or agreed services, or exhibit the
dwelling unit to prospective or actual purchasers, mortgagees,
tenants, workers, or contractors or to make an inspection pursuant to
subdivision (f) of Section 1950.5.
(3) When the tenant has abandoned or surrendered the premises.
(4) Pursuant to court order.
(b) Except in cases of emergency or when the tenant has abandoned
or surrendered the premises, entry may not be made during other than
normal business hours unless the tenant consents to an entry during
other than normal business hours at the time of entry.
(c) The landlord may not abuse the right of access or use it to
harass the tenant.
(d) (1) Except as provided in subdivision (e), or as provided in
paragraph (2) or (3), the landlord shall give the tenant reasonable
notice in writing of his or her intent to enter and enter only during
normal business hours. The notice shall include the date,
approximate time, and purpose of the entry. The notice may be
personally delivered to the tenant, left with someone of a suitable
age and discretion at the premises, or, left on, near, or under the
usual entry door of the premises in a manner in which a reasonable
person would discover the notice. Twenty-four hours shall be presumed
to be reasonable notice in absence of evidence to the contrary. The
notice may be mailed to the tenant. Mailing of the notice at least
six days prior to an intended entry is presumed reasonable notice in
the absence of evidence to the contrary.
(2) If the purpose of the entry is to exhibit the dwelling unit to
prospective or actual purchasers, the notice may be given orally, in
person or by telephone, if the landlord or his or her agent has
notified the tenant in writing within 120 days of the oral notice
that the property is for sale and that the landlord or agent may
contact the tenant orally for the purpose described above.
Twenty-four hours is presumed reasonable notice in the absence of
evidence to the contrary. The notice shall include the date,
approximate time, and purpose of the entry. At the time of entry, the
landlord or agent shall leave written evidence of the entry inside
the unit.
(3) The tenant and the landlord may agree orally to an entry to
make agreed repairs or supply agreed services. The agreement shall
include the date and approximate time of the entry, which shall be
within one week of the agreement. In this case, the landlord is not
required to provide the tenant a written notice.
(e) No notice of entry is required under this section:
(1) To respond to an emergency.
(2) If the tenant is present and consents to the entry at the time
of entry.
(3) After the tenant has abandoned or surrendered the unit.<//review><GmapID>0x808327ac6558c5ad:0x43e58a08e2365cd6<//GmapID><resp>None</resp>< Rate>

4</rating>
< review>
It's ironic that this edifice built to suppress 'anarchists' should host the Anarchist Book Fair, but they do. It's also ironic that certain anarchists choose to boycott because this is arguably the largest niche film production studio in San Francisco. You can take a tour and watch films in the making. The tour price may seem steep (to me, anyway) but there are frequent 2 for 1 offers. American Conservatory Theater has presented a play here. Skateboarders give the front steps five stars and the walls are popular with urban ninjas.< /review>

We visited different sets on multiple floors including Dungeon (basement) and learned about history of the building, how it became home to not-a-movie studio and how it is being used these days.
Through the tour you will learn about porn studio operations, hiring, policies, workshops, community e.t.c.

< text>
R.e. their tour: Right from the start our tour guide Dane was a wonderful orator.
There was eight of us on the tour which was just the right size to be personal (I think they take up to thirty).

Despite being billed for ninety minutes we ran a little over (which was great, as I didn't want it to end!).
Dane was very conscientious the whole time, and never made us feel out of place. A wide range of subjects were covered from the building, to the company, to his personal accounts of what goes on 'behind the scenes'.
Asking questions was encouraged, never felt awkward, and always replied to in an knowledgeable and interesting way.

I would recommend to anyone with even the slightest interest!<//text>

<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
The food here is amazing. Beautifully plated and most importantly, absolutely delicious. Highly recommend ordering the crostini for a starter. <userid>106119317949444657942</userid><Name>David Gray<//Name><date>1545243285637<//date><rate>5< /rate>< Text>
My wife has been wearing hearing aids for more than 25 years but her hearing has still slowly deteriorated. Her three-year-old hearing aids were helping but still so much sound, especially speech differentiation, was just lost to her. She read several articles about the Oticon Opn hearing aid, its new technology and the real success hearing loss sufferers had exxperienced with it. We were interested in more information about the Oticon product but Diane had not been particularly impressed with the level of interest or effort her most recent audiologist provided so we began to research hearing aid distributors. Thankfully, we read about Doug Wesson and his hearing aid centers in and around Manteca. Diane called for an appointment and was able to go to the Ripon location the next day. No money was exchanged but she left Wesson's office that day with Oticon Opn demo hearing aids to try! We never expected that kind of service. Diane wore the hearing aids a week and experienced life altering improvement in her ability to hear - and more importantly - to undertand speech. She hears things like rain and the furnace running now. She is delighted both with these new hearing aids and with Doug Wesson and his whole staff for their nonflagging support. If you have hearing aids that still leave you working too hard to try to understand speech, or most especially, if you have hearing loss but have never invested in hearing devices, we wholeheartedly recommend the new Oticon Opn product paired with the kindness and experience of the folks at Wesson Hearing Aid Center.<//Text>

I have used a couple of the other auto body shops in the Paso Robles area and had some disappointing results. When it came time to have work done on my own company truck, after a deer jumped in front of it, I decided to give Autocraft a shot. Best decision I could have made for many reasons: communication, quality, timeliness and courteous. I was always informed and updated by the service writers assigned to my truck. Everyone is really friendly and eager to keep you satisfied; from the folks in the office to the guys taking care of the repairs in the shop. < Text>
Some how something had sprayed on the paint of my BMW and I had about 40 small spots which had eaten through the clear coat into the paint. This was on the hood, top, and trunk.I filed a claim and my insurance company and they denied it saying that it was just normal ware from driving around. Four months later, a friend recommended Auto Craft Collision to have a look at the paint damage. I met with Derek, he looked at the problem and he said it was some type of caustic material that most likely came from another vehicle on the freeway. I contacted my insurance company again with Derek's opinion and his photos of the damage and they accepted the claim to repair and repaint the vehicle. Auto Craft didn't just tape off things to paint around lights ect, they disassembled a lot of the vehicle to paint panels and around the edges. Their workmanship is of the highest standards and the car looks like new. Had it not been for Derek, I never would have got this repaired. He worked on my behalf with the insurance and got everything taken care of. A big thanks to Derek.</Text>
